Contrary to what is often implied, Morrowind wasn't some groundbreaking game at the time. Mechanics-wise it was middle of the road, and a lot of the gameplay was pretty standard stuff. What set Morrowind apart from everyone else was the world, it just had a vibe that couldn't be met by anyone else.

Deus Ex (also from that era) had the same thing going on. Pretty neat gameplay mechanics in that one, (especially when you compare it to the infuriating shit going on in System Shock 2) but man was it moody and cool. I remember picking up Morrowind after a long time playing Elder Scrolls games (I still have the floppies somewhere around here) and man it was a cut above them in a lot of ways. Unfortunately, it seemed dumbed-down compared to Daggerfall, but at the time I didn't think much about it until the potato-faced dogshit known as Oblivion came out.

As someone who played it upon release, I'd say it's one of those rare games that holds up. There are some disappointing old-isms, such as elemental damage really only mattering for immunities, or most quests being in the "go there, do this" format. But the game really leans on a well built world and setting. Vvardenfell somehow feels alive despite the NPC's always standing in the same locations. It's little stuff, like the South of the island being clearly more hospitable and more densely populated, as opposed to Skyrim's neat one detailed city per large hold with its one tiny village somewhere near.

>>69179670
Deus Ex is another one of those games that holds up well. It's all smart design, some of which still hasn't been topped.
